The anti-aging industry is filled with exaggerated promises, expensive powders, and herbs marketed like miracles.

Most of it is noise.

But a smaller group of plants repeatedly survived across generations because people kept using them long before modern wellness culture existed. Some later attracted serious scientific interest around:
- oxidative stress
- inflammation
- collagen
- circulation
- skin aging
- long-term resilience

No herb stops aging.

But some herbs genuinely appear more promising than others.

## Green Tea (Camellia sinensis)

Green tea developed one of the strongest longevity reputations in the world long before antioxidant research existed.

In China and Japan, it was consumed daily for centuries as part of ordinary life rather than as a “biohack.” Modern researchers later became interested in catechins and polyphenols, especially EGCG.

Why people use it:
- Rich in antioxidant compounds
- Associated with skin protection
- Studied for oxidative stress and inflammation
- Connected with long-term daily wellness practices

Best method:

- Use loose leaf green tea
- Avoid boiling water
- Steep 2–3 minutes
- Drink regularly rather than excessively

Traditional tea cultures generally emphasized consistency over intensity.

---

## Gotu Kola (Centella asiatica)

Gotu kola developed one of the strongest traditional reputations for aging well, tissue repair, and connective tissue support.

In Ayurvedic and Southeast Asian herbal traditions, it became associated with skin recovery, circulation, memory, and longevity.

Modern skincare research later became interested in its relationship to collagen and wound healing.

Why people use it:
- Associated with collagen and connective tissue
- Traditionally used for circulation support
- Studied for skin elasticity and repair
- Connected with long-term vitality practices

Best method:

- Drink as tea or infusion
- Use fresh leaves when possible
- Can also be infused into oils and skin preparations

Gotu kola developed a reputation for gradual long-term support rather than dramatic short-term effects.

---

## Turmeric (Curcuma longa)

Turmeric became one of the most historically respected herbs for inflammation support.

Across South Asia, it was used in food, ritual cleansing, skin care, and household medicine centuries before modern supplement culture existed.

Modern research later focused heavily on curcumin and inflammation pathways.

Why people use it:
- Associated with inflammation support
- Traditionally used for skin and joint health
- Commonly included in longevity-focused diets
- Historically used both internally and externally

Best method:

- Combine with black pepper and fat
- Add to food, broths, or warm milk
- Use moderate amounts consistently

Traditional food preparation already paired turmeric with oils and spices long before absorption studies explained why.

---

## Ginseng (Panax ginseng)

Few herbs became as strongly associated with vitality and resilience as ginseng.

In East Asian herbal traditions, older roots were sometimes valued so highly they became gifts, status symbols, and guarded medicinal treasures.

Its reputation centered around endurance, recovery, strength, and aging well under stress.

Why people use it:
- Traditionally associated with vitality and stamina
- Studied for stress resilience and circulation
- Connected with skin vitality and recovery
- Long history as a longevity herb

Best method:

- Decoction or long steeped tea
- Small consistent doses rather than excessive use
- Traditionally taken over long periods

Historically, ginseng was often viewed as a strengthening herb rather than a quick stimulant.

---

## Astragalus (Astragalus membranaceus)

Astragalus developed one of the deepest longevity reputations in traditional Chinese herbalism.

Rather than being viewed as a beauty herb, it became associated with resilience, recovery capacity, and preserving strength over time.

Modern research later became interested in astragalus compounds connected with immune function, oxidative stress, and cellular aging pathways.

Why people use it:
- Traditionally associated with longevity
- Connected with resilience and recovery
- Studied for oxidative stress and immune support
- Often included in long-term tonic formulas

Best method:

- Simmer sliced root in soups or decoctions
- Combine with broths and tonic herbs
- Use regularly over time

Astragalus was traditionally used more like a food-medicine than a dramatic short-term remedy.

